7.03 | 1865 Gregor Mendel showed that traits are controlled by discrete factors now known as genes. | | 
7.03 | 1869 Friedrich Miescher isolated DNA from the nuclei of white blood cells. | | 
7.03 | 1903 Walter Sutton and Theodor Boveri hypothesized that chromosomes are the hereditary elements. | | 
7.03 | 1905 William Bateson introduced the term “genetics” for the study of inheritance. | | 
7.03 | 1908 G. H. Hardy and Wilhelm Weinberg proposed the Hardy–Weinberg law, the foundation for population genetics. | | 
7.03 | 1910 Thomas H. Morgan demonstrated that genes are located on chromosomes. | | 
7.03 | 1913 Alfred Sturtevant made a genetic linkage map of the Drosophila X chromosome, the first genetic map. | | 
7.03 | 1918 Ronald Fisher proposed that multiple Mendelian factors can explain continuous variation for traits, founding the field of quantitative genetics. | | 
7.03 | 1931 Harriet Creighton and Barbara McClintock showed that crossing over is the cause of recombination. | | 
7.03 | 1941 Edward Tatum and George Beadle proposed the one-gene—one-polypeptide hypothesis. | | 
7.03 | 1944 Oswald Avery, Colin MacLeod, and Maclyn McCarty provided compelling evidence that DNA is the genetic material in bacterial cells. | | 
7.03 | 1946 Joshua Lederberg and Edward Tatum discovered bacterial conjugation. | | 
7.03 | 1948 Barbara McClintock discovered mobile elements (transposons) that move from one place to another in the genome. | | 
7.03 | 1950 Erwin Chargaff showed DNA composition follows some simple rules for the relative amounts of A, C, G, and T. | | 
7.03 | 1952 Alfred Hershey and Martha Chase proved that DNA is the molecule that encodes genetic information. | | 
7.03 | 1958 Matthew Meselson and Franklin Stahl demonstrated the semiconservative nature of DNA replication. | | 
7.03 | 1961 François Jacob and Jacques Monod proposed that enzyme levels in cells are controlled by feedback mechanisms. | | 
7.03 | 1967 Marshall Nirenberg, Har Gobind Khorana, Sydney Brenner, and Francis Crick "cracked" the genetic code. | | 
7.03 | 1968 Motoo Kimura proposed the neutral theory of molecular evolution. | | 
7.03 | 1977 Fred Sanger, Walter Gilbert, and Allan Maxam invented methods for determining the nucleotide sequences of DNA molecules. | | 
7.03 | 1980 Christiane Nüsslein-Volhard and Eric F. Wieschaus defined the complex of genes that regulate body plan development in Drosophila. | | 
7.03 | 1989 Francis Collins and Lap-Chee Tsui discovered the gene causing cystic fibrosis. | | 
7.03 | 1993 Victor Ambrose and colleagues described the first microRNA. | | 
7.03 | 1995 First genome sequence of a living organism (Haemophilus influenzae) published. | | 
7.03 | 1996 First genome sequence of a eukaryote (Saccharomyces cerevisiae) published. | | 
7.03 | 1998 First genome sequence of an animal (Caenorhabditis elegans) published. | | 
7.03 | 2000 First genome sequence of a plant (Arabidopsis thaliana) published. | | 
7.03 | 2001 The sequence of the human genome first published. | | 
7.03 | 2006 Andrew Fire and Craig Mello win the Nobel prize for their discovery of gene silencing by double-stranded RNA. | | 
7.03 | 2012 John Gurdon and Shinya Yamanaka win the Nobel prize for their discovery that just four regulatory genes can convert adult cells into stem cells. | | 
